stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> starting: Docker "start" event
    starting --> healthy: health_status healthy / no healthcheck configured (null)
    healthy --> unhealthy: health_status unhealthy
    unhealthy --> healthy: health_status healthy (self-recovered or auto-heal restart succeeded)
    unhealthy --> died: "die" event
    starting --> died: "die" event
    healthy --> died: "die" event
    died --> destroyed: "destroy" event
    healthy --> destroyed: "destroy" event
    unhealthy --> destroyed: "destroy" event

    state unhealthy {
        [*] --> heal_idle
        heal_idle --> heal_cooldown_check
        heal_cooldown_check --> heal_jitter_wait: within cooldown or attempts<3
        heal_cooldown_check --> heal_gave_up: attempts >= HEAL_MAX_ATTEMPTS (3)
        heal_jitter_wait --> heal_attempting: jitter elapsed [0-3s], calls containerlab restart --node
        heal_attempting --> heal_idle: restart succeeded (health-update resets heal state)
        heal_attempting --> heal_backoff_wait: restart failed
        heal_backoff_wait --> heal_jitter_wait: exponential backoff elapsed (base 5s, factor 3, cap 60s)
    }

    note right of heal_attempting
        containerlab restart is an in-place Docker
        restart (stop+start), not a recreate, so the
        container ID is preserved across a heal cycle.
        Chosen deliberately over redeploy for this reason.
    end note
